It must be added that the Epistolary form becomes in some cases a matter of play-as when he makes a prosessed letter to his bailiff the vehiele lor the humorous expression os his own love of the country and dislike oi restlessness (Ep. 14); when he puts an apology to Augustus into the form os a letter sent after the mes· senger who is supposed to be carrying to him a volume os poems (Ep. 13) ; or when he addresses to his own Book of collected Epistles the confidences and anticipations which he means sor his world-wide audiencetobe (Ep. ιο).

In calling his Epistles ‘Sermones’ he is expressing the continuity in substance, and even in form, which unites the most important os them, those sor the sake os which the book was written, to the Satires. Their subject is the same, that which always interested him most deeply,-the art of lis . It runs into the same topics, the folly of aranee, the wisdom of enjoying instead of wishing, the charm of country life, of moderate tastes, of contentment. He fingere amusedly‚ as before, the paradoxes of philosophers, and puts even more conlidently his view that more is to be learnt from common sense and from the poets than in the schools. The style is the same-the iree and unrhetorical style ol the best conversation, playsul and serious by turns, lighted up by wit, good humour, touches of poetry. It still cuts an argument short with an anecdote or a table. There is the same tendency to use an individual name where a class is meant, and in doing so to mix indiscriminately names oi the day with literary or even mythological reminis- cences ¹. The epistolary form is in truth as much a dramatic adaptation as the form of dialogue adopted in Book 11 of the Satires. As Acron remarks, it is conversation still, conversation with the absent instead os conversation held or overheard, with the present: ‘Epistulis enirn ad absentes loquimur, sermone cum prae· sentibus ²!
